e up with a new invention that weakens the quantum electromagnetic covalent bond of the atomic structure of molecules in water H2O. In water molecules the oxygen atom attracts the electrons in an OH covalent bond, the hydrogen has no inner shell of electrons to shield the nucleus and there is an electrostatic interaction between the hydrogen proton and the single pair of electrons on the oxygen atom in the associate molecules. Each oxygen atom has two associates pairs of electrons and can make hydrogen bond to two different hydrogen atoms. The strengths of hydrogen bonds are about one tenth of the strengths of normal covalent bonds. Hydrogen bonding does have significant effects on physical properties. It accounts for the unusual properties of water and for the relatively high boiling point of H2O, HF, and NH3 compared with H2S, HC1 and PH3."We have come up with a new device that weakens the covalent bond in water H2O molecules making it much easier to split water into hydrogen in larger quantities in a shorter time period. This new apparatus does not include more energy in to produce hydrogen it requires less energy in to split water into hydrogen.  No new energy is required to weaken the covalent bong of the water molecules. We expect to have the new reactor ready for testing in the next two weeks. We already have CSRV® engines operating on water split into hydrogen so we know it works."The Chinese New Year starts today. We believe it will go on for two weeks. We are ready to go when they are. Letters of Intent, preliminary agreements and nondisclosure agreements have all been signed and will be posted on our EDGAR filings.The Company is continuing talks with financers here in the USA for funding the start up of production here in America.Orders are still coming in for our natural gas industrial CSRV® engine generators from the oil and gas industry. We are now requesting 50% deposits with five months delivery time.We are hoping to have our products out in the market place in 2014. This will enhance the Company value and benefit our shareholders and all involved.There can be no assurance made that the Company will be successful in any of its endeavors.This press release contains forward-looking statements that are made pursuant to the safe harbor provisions of the Private Securities Litigation Reform Act of 1995. Our public filings with the SEC may be viewed and printed from the website maintained by the SEC at http://www.sec.gov.Thursday, January 2, 2014 8:00 AM ETCOATES INTERNATIONAL, LTD IS PLEASED TO ANNOUNCE THAT COMPANY PRESIDENT AND CEO MR. GEORGE J. COATES IS TO VISIT CHINA FOR MEETINGS WITH GOVERNMENT OFFICIALS REGARDING ESTABLISHING MASS PRODUCTION OPERATIONS OF CSRV PRODUCTS IN CHINA. IT IS ANTICIPATED THAT OVER $1,500,000,000 WILL BE INVESTED IN THE PROJECT OVER A RELATIVELY SHORT TERM. PRELIMINARY AGREEMENTS AND LETTERS OF INTENT HAVE ALREADY BEEN EXECUTED.The President and CEO is to visit China to meet with government officials and business executives from Chinese manufacturing companies involved in  establishing mass production operations of the Coates CSRV® products in China for distribution throughout Europe, the Far East, and the UAE. Investments in this project are expected to exceed $1,500,000,000. Many Coates products are to be produced including retrofit kits for many makes of engines including heavy trucks, busses, marine applications and more.Mr. Coates comments, “A lot of work and time has gone into this project. We must forge ahead as markets are opening up for our CSRV® products. Just think of it, we eliminate 2,700 parts and components of an industrial 6 cylinder engine and replace them with only two rotating CSRV® shafts and 12 floating seals and eliminate the oil service to the head of the engine. On a V12 engine we would eliminate approximately 6,400 components and parts. The production costs of all these parts and assembly is extremely costly but the CSRV® system could be approximately one tent